<P><HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=CENTER><P>

<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="10"><H1><STRONG>Small Business Law
</STRONG></H1></A></CENTER>
A small business can take a variety of forms, including a sole proprietorship, general partnership, limited partnership, or corporation. Though a small business may not have the assets of a larger company, it is still governed by many of the same laws and is frequently in need of legal advice. This chapter provides a brief overview of some of the forms of business. For a more detailed discussion of these and other business-related issues, consult the <STRONG><A HREF="../../flhome.html">Law &amp; Leading Attorneys: Florida Business Guide</A></STRONG> or an attorney.
<P>
Whatever the form, the first step in properly organizing a small business is developing a written business plan, setting out the objectives to be obtained, methods to be used in reaching those objectives, rules and regulations that will govern the business, projected expenses, insurance needs, and a host of other considerations. It is recommended that a person consult an attorney when writing his or her business plan.
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="20"><H2><STRONG>Sole Proprietorship</STRONG></H2></A></CENTER>
A <STRONG>sole proprietorship</STRONG> is the most basic business organization. One person (the sole proprietor) owns, manages, and controls the business. There is no distinction between the personal assets of the sole proprietor and those of the business. 
<P>
Setting up a sole proprietorship is less complicated than setting up other forms of business, but still requires obtaining certain approvals, registrations, licenses and insurance, as well as tax identification numbers. A sole proprietor should also know whether the area in which he or she is operating is zoned for business. Some sole proprietors working out of their homes may be in violation of local zoning ordinances. 
<P>
If a sole proprietor is doing business under a name other than his or her legal name, the sole proprietor must register the "fictitious" name with the Division of Corporations of the Florida Secretary of State (see the <A HREF="#150">Resources</A> section below for more information). The cost of registering is $50 and the registration certificate is good for five years. Sole proprietors wishing to renew their registration must do so prior to the end of the five-year period. Failure to register is a second degree misdemeanor. 
<P>
To dissolve a sole proprietorship a person just has to cease doing business. Unlike a corporation, however, a sole proprietor is personally liable for any unpaid debts. An unlucky sole proprietor may have to empty a personal savings account or sell a house to pay creditors. Personal liability is the principal drawback to forming a sole proprietorship. But there are also benefits. Sole proprietors enjoy the freedom of running their own show and not having to answer to disgruntled shareholders or partners. (Another means of enjoying the same freedom is to create a corporation with only one director and one shareholder. See <A HREF="#90">Corporation</A> below.) 
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="30"><H2><STRONG>Partnership</STRONG></H2></A></CENTER>
A <STRONG>partnership</STRONG> is a business owned by two or more persons. Like a sole proprietorship, a partnership is not a separate legal entity and the partners can be held personally liable for the debts of the partnership. This includes one partner being held liable for the indebtedness of the entire partnership. Partnerships, however, can hold title to land in the name of the partnership. Partnerships can also be sued in the name of the partnership, but any suits by the partnership must be in the name of the individual partners. 
<P>
<A NAME="40"><H3><STRONG>Formation</STRONG></H3></A>
Forming a partnership is a relatively straightforward process. Aside from obtaining the necessary approvals, registrations, licenses, insurance, and tax numbers, and registering the business name with the Division of Corporations of the Florida Secretary of State (if different than the legal names of the partners), the partners must agree on the treatment of profits, expenses, losses, contributions to the partnership, and other business concerns. This is usually accomplished by all partners signing a partnership agreement. Though a written partnership agreement is not necessary, it is strongly recommended. 
<P>
<A NAME="50"><H3><STRONG>Relations Between the Partners</STRONG></H3></A>
Unless otherwise agreed, all partners are assumed to have equal rights in the management of the business. Each partner owes a fiduciary duty to the partnership, which means he or she must act primarily for the benefit of the partnership in all partnership-related matters. All business profits belong to the partnership and not to individual partners. Moreover, partners are generally not paid for their efforts since they receive a portion of the partnership profits. 
<P>
When making partnership-related contracts or incurring debts, each partner has the authority to bind the partnership. An injured third party has the right to collect debts from one or all of the partners as he or she sees fit. Partners are not usually permitted to sue the partnership (nor vice-versa) since the two are interrelated and a partner can be liable for the debts of the partnership. A partner would in effect be suing him or herself if he or she sued the partnership. 
<P>
<A NAME="60"><H3><STRONG>Dissolution</STRONG></H3></A>
A partnership can be dissolved by the parties, by law, or by a court decree. If the partners agree to dissolve the partnership, expel a partner, or if the partnership contract sets a definite term to the partnership (and the term has expired), the partnership is dissolved. 
<P>
Under Florida law, a partnership can be dissolved if the partnership's activity is unlawful, if one of the partners dies (though a new partnership can be created), or if the partnership is bankrupt. Finally, if one of the partners petitions a court to dissolve the partnership, the partnership will be dissolved if the court finds a sufficient reason (e.g., breach of partnership agreement, misconduct, incompetence, unprofitability). 
<P>
Like a sole proprietorship, when a partnership dissolves, the partners remain liable for any unpaid debts. If any assets remain, the partners divide them in proportion to their interest in the partnership or as the partnership agreement provides.
<P>
<A NAME="70"><H3><STRONG>Pros and Cons of Partnership</STRONG></H3></A>
The chief benefit of a partnership over a sole proprietorship is the availability of more financing and ideas, and the sharing of responsibilities. Unlike a sole proprietorship, a partnership is a team effort. A partnership may be a less complicated form of organization than a corporation or a limited partnership (see below). Finally, profits from the partnership are included on the partners' individual tax returns and taxed at the individual taxpayer rate, which might be lower than the rate charged to a corporation (unless the shareholders of that corporation elect Subchapter S tax treatment).
<P>
One of the chief drawbacks to a partnership is the partners' personal liability for the debts of the partnership. Also, partners do not enjoy the exclusive control that a sole proprietor does (or that the owner of a corporation with only one director and shareholder does) and partners cannot deduct employment benefits, such as health and dental insurance, from their income tax returns as business expenses.
<P>
<A NAME="80"><H3><STRONG>Limited Partnerships</STRONG></H3></A>
A <STRONG>limited partnership</STRONG> is made up of general partners and limited partners. A <STRONG>limited partner</STRONG> is similar to a shareholder of a corporation. Unlike a general partner, a limited partner shares in the profits of a limited partnership, but is usually not personally liable for any losses beyond his or her investment. 
<P>
To form a limited partnership a certificate must be filed with the Division of Corporations of the Florida Secretary of State stating, among other things, (1) the name and mailing address of the limited partnership; (2) the name and address of each general partner (limited partners do not have to be included); and (3) the latest date upon which the partnership is to dissolve. An affidavit stating the limited partners' capital contributions must accompany the certificate. The limited partnership must also appoint a registered agent and have a written partnership agreement. 
<P>
The name of a limited partnership must contain the word "Limited" or the abbreviation "Ltd." Also, the name of any limited partner cannot be used in the partnership name unless it is also the name of a general partner or if business has previously been conducted with that name as part of the title. The purpose of the name restriction is to protect the public from believing a limited partner is a member of a general partnership and therefore personally liable for partnership debts.
<P>
It is important to note that state approval to use a name by a limited partnership is no guarantee that use of the name will not cause damage to another business or person with a similar name.
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="90"><H2><STRONG>Corporation</STRONG></H2></A></CENTER>
A properly created and operated corporation is, in the eyes of the law, the creation and operation of another person. Unlike a sole proprietorship or general partnership, a corporation is a separate legal entity from its owners. A corporation can make purchases, enter into contracts, pay taxes, borrow money, and sue and be sued in its own name. 
<P>
The principal benefit of a corporation is a limitation on liability. A corporation's owners (the shareholders) are not personally liable for the debts of a corporation, with certain exceptions, some of which can be covered by insurance. In this way, the law encourages people to form and invest in corporations. 
<P>
<A NAME="100"><H3><STRONG>Structure</STRONG></H3></A>
On a basic level, a corporation is made up of owners and operators. The owners are <STRONG>shareholders</STRONG> whose interests in the corporation are represented by the amount and type of <STRONG>stock</STRONG> owned. A shareholder pays the corporation a set price in exchange for a share of stock. The more stock a shareholder owns, the more of the corporation he or she owns. The operators of the corporation are the <STRONG>officers</STRONG> (e.g., president, vice president, secretary, treasurer). The officers administer the day-to-day affairs of the corporation. 
<P>
A corporation also has a <STRONG>board of directors</STRONG> which is elected by the shareholders. The directors oversee the work of the officers and make certain that the money supplied by the shareholders is being used efficiently. If the officers are doing their job, the corporation turns a profit, the value of the corporation increases, which means the value of the stock increases. If a corporation turns a profit, it may issue a dividend to shareholders. A <STRONG>dividend</STRONG> is a percentage of the corporation's profits based upon the number of shares of stock a shareholder owns. On the other hand, if the officers are making poor decisions or if the corporation is suffering for other reasons, the value of the corporation's stock falls.
<P>
<A NAME="110"><H3><STRONG>Formation</STRONG></H3></A>
Florida has specific guidelines for the formation of a corporation. Generally, a corporate group must file its Articles of Incorporation with the Division of Corporations of the Florida Department of State. The <STRONG>articles of incorporation</STRONG> usually contain, among other things, the name of the corporation, the total number of shares of stock that the corporation is authorized to issue, the value of an individual share of stock, the address of the corporation's registered office, and the purposes for which the corporation is organized. The corporate name must include the word "corporation," "company," "incorporated," or some abbreviation thereof indicating that the business is incorporated. The corporation must file with the Division of Corporations an appointment and acceptance of its registered agent. 
<P>
After payment of the requisite fees and taxes, the Division of Corporations will notify the corporation of its acceptance of the articles of incorporation, provided the corporate name is not already taken or otherwise conflicts with the name of another corporation. As pointed out above, approval of the name is no guarantee that it can be used without damage to a person or another business. After acceptance of the articles of incorporation, and when certain other conditions are met, the corporation holds organizational meetings, elects directors, passes bylaws, issues stock, elects officers and hires other employees, etc. 
<P>
<A NAME="120"><H3><STRONG>Pros and Cons of Incorporation</STRONG></H3></A>
Aside from some protection of limited liability, the corporate form can provide a number of other benefits. A corporation can provide for continuity of existence. Despite the departure of officers or directors, or the selling of stock by shareholders, a corporation can continue to exist. Such corporations will continue to exist until dissolved involuntarily, or by court order. For example, a corporation can be dissoved by the Secretary of State for failure to file its annual report. Corporations also have access to capital markets. By selling stock, corporations can raise capital. A corporation can sell stock privately or publicly on stock exchanges such as the New York Stock Exchange (upon compliance with applicable security laws). 
<P>
The principal drawback to a corporation is double taxation. A corporation must file its own tax returns and pay taxes on profits. Shareholders must also pay taxes on any dividend received from the corporation.
<P>
<A NAME="130"><H3><STRONG>Subchapter S Corporation</STRONG></H3></A>
Small businesses may want to qualify as <STRONG>Subchapter S corporations</STRONG> by filing a proper election with the IRS. In this case, the corporation itself is not usually taxed, but its taxable income is taxed directly to the shareholders in proportion to their stock holdings. Thus, the shareholders may receive the benefit of limited liability, without double taxation of corporate earnings distributed as dividends. The requirements for qualifying as a Subchapter S corporation include:
<UL>
<LI>No more than 35 shareholders
<LI>Shareholders must be natural persons (not corporations or partnerships)
<LI>Shareholders cannot be non-residents 
<LI>One class of stock
<LI>All shareholders must consent in writing to Subchapter S treatment
</UL>
<P>
<A NAME="140"><H3><STRONG>Non-profit Corporation</STRONG></H3></A>
A <STRONG>non-profit corporation</STRONG> is organized for purposes other than distributing profits to its shareholders. Many charitable or social welfare organizations are organized as non-profit corporations. Unions are also sometimes organized as non-profit corporations. Non-profit corporations are accorded special treatment under federal and state law, including tax exemption, provided certain requirements are met. 
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="150"><H2><STRONG>Resources</STRONG></H2></A></CENTER>
The Division of Corporations of the Florida Department of State can be contacted by writing to P.O. Box 6327, Tallahassee, FL 32314 or calling (904) 488-9000.

<P>
The federal Small Business Administration, which provides loans and technical assistance to small businesses, has two district offices in Florida. The Coral Gables office can be contacted at (305) 536-5521 and the Jacksonville office at (904) 443-1900.

<P>
The Florida Small Business Development Center Network provides free and confidential one-on-one counseling in a variety of areas including business start-up, financial and cash flow analysis, loan packaging, accounting and record keeping, marketing and sales, energy conservation, and international trade. There are small business development centers located around the state.<P>
