<P>
<H1><CENTER>State Bar Associations</CENTER>
</H1>
<P><HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=CENTER><P>



A bar or a bar association is a body of attorneys and judges authorized to practice in a particular jurisdiction. A bar can be local, statewide, or national. Bar associations can be voluntary (i.e., an attorney is not required to be a member in order to practice law in the jurisdiction) or mandatory (i.e., every attorney wishing to practice in the jurisdiction must be a member). One of the principal responsibilities of a bar association is attorney regulation and assuring that attorneys are abiding by the ethical and professional guidelines governing attorney conduct.
<P>
It is important to keep in mind that laws can vary drastically from state to state. Many state bar associations refer callers to member attorneys and several will provide basic summaries of state laws, free of charge. Below is a list of state bar associations around the country. Note that a few states have more than one bar association listed.
<P><HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=CENTER><P>

